Each cell along the railway tracks consists of two states, namely active and passive. Because there is a high risk to powering off the radio unit in a cellular railway network, the passive state uses a time slot power-saving strategy [24], which was designed to reduce the energy consumption on the idle time slot. The strategy is to adjust the power amplifier bias to a much lower level when no traffic is on the carrier. When the cell is controlled to be in an energy-saving mode by the BSC node, the corresponding cell enters into the passive state; otherwise, it stays in the active state, which is described as follows:1ci=1Active,BSisnotinpowersavingmode0Passive,BSisinpowersavingmode\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
